class SeatManager {
public:
    SeatManager(int n) {
        seats = vector<int>(n, 0);
    }

    int reserve() {
        int seatNumber = find_available_seat();
        seats[seatNumber] = 1;
        return seatNumber;
    }

    void unreserve(int seatNumber) {
        seats[seatNumber] = 0;
    }

    int find_available_seat() {
        for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
            if (seats[i] == 0) {
                return i;
            }
        }
        return -1; // No available seats found
    }

    void update_seats() {
        for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
            seats[i] = 0;
        }
    }

    private:
    vector<int> seats;
};
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW

Explanation:

The solution uses a vector to store the state of each seat (reserved or not). The reserve() function finds the first available seat by iterating through the vector and checking if a seat is available. If an available seat is found, it returns the seat number. If no seat is available, it returns -1. The update_seats() function iterates through the vector and sets all seats to available (0).

The efficiency is high because the reserve() function only iterates through the vector once, and the update_seats() function iterates through the vector once. The space complexity is O(1) because the vector has a constant space complexity. The energy implications are low because the algorithm does not consume any significant energy.

